---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const slug = 'hormones-analogs';
const displayName = 'Hormones and Analogs';

const drugs = (drugsData as any[]).filter(
  (d: any) => (d.therapeutic_classes || []).includes(slug)
);
const drugCount = drugs.length;
---
<SchemaLayout title="Hormones and Analogs" schema="therapeutic-classes" description="Endogenous hormones, synthetic analogs, and hormone-modifying agents used in replacement therapy and disease management">

  <div class="mb-6">
    <div class="breadcrumbs text-sm mb-4">
      <ul>
        <li><a href={`${base}schemas/02-therapeutic-classes/`} class="link">Therapeutic Classes</a></li>
        <li>{displayName}</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-base-content mb-2">{displayName}</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">{drugCount} drug{drugCount !== 1 ? 's' : ''} in this class</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>Hormones and their pharmacological analogs represent nature's own signaling molecules repurposed as therapeutic agents, a strategy that predates rational drug design: the administration of thyroid extract for myxedema dates to 1891, and the purification of insulin by Banting and Best in 1921 transformed type 1 diabetes from a fatal wasting disease to a manageable chronic condition. The development of synthetic hormone analogs—structurally modified derivatives of endogenous hormones—has extended this approach dramatically, allowing pharmacokinetic engineering (prolonged half-lives, altered routes of administration), receptor subtype selectivity (estrogen receptor modulators, glucocorticoid-specific ligands), and enhanced potency. Hormone pharmacology spans the major endocrine axes: the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis (corticosteroids), hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis (levothyroxine, methimazole), hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis (estrogens, progestins, androgens, GnRH analogs), pancreatic endocrine function (insulins, glucagon, incretin mimetics), and parathyroid-bone homeostasis (teriparatide, denosumab, bisphosphonates). Each axis requires nuanced understanding of feedback regulation, pulsatility, and circadian rhythmicity that governs both therapeutic efficacy and safety.</p>
    <p>The molecular mechanisms of hormone action are determined by receptor type and subcellular location. Nuclear receptor ligands—glucocorticoids (cortisol, prednisone, dexamethasone), mineralocorticoids (aldosterone, fludrocortisone), thyroid hormones (levothyroxine), sex steroids (estradiol, testosterone, progesterone)—bind intracellular receptors that translocate to the nucleus and act as transcription factors, altering gene expression with onset of hours to days rather than minutes. This genomic mechanism explains why systemic glucocorticoids require 6–24 hours to produce their full anti-inflammatory effect, and why chronic high-dose glucocorticoid administration suppresses the HPA axis and causes adrenal atrophy within weeks, creating dependence and the potential for adrenal crisis on abrupt discontinuation. Peptide hormones—insulin, glucagon, GLP-1 analogs (liraglutide, semaglutide), oxytocin—bind cell-surface receptors (RTKs, GPCRs) and activate second-messenger cascades with rapid onset of minutes; their peptide nature renders them orally inactive due to proteolytic degradation and necessitates parenteral or transmucosal administration. Insulin activates the insulin receptor tyrosine kinase, which phosphorylates IRS proteins to activate PI3K-Akt signaling, promoting GLUT4 translocation to the cell surface, glycogen synthesis, lipogenesis, and protein anabolism—effects that collectively define insulin as an anabolic hormone.</p>
    <p>The pharmacokinetics of hormones and analogs are engineered to match clinical requirements. Insulin analogs are designed to alter absorption kinetics from the subcutaneous injection site: rapid-acting analogs (lispro, aspart, glulisine) have single amino acid substitutions that prevent hexamer formation, allowing faster monomer absorption with onset of 15 minutes and duration of 3–4 hours suitable for mealtime dosing; long-acting analogs (glargine, detemir, degludec) form depot precipitates or albumin-bound complexes at the injection site that dissolve slowly, producing flat, peakless profiles lasting 20–42 hours. Thyroid hormone replacement with levothyroxine (T4) exploits peripheral deiodination to T3 as the source of biological activity, resulting in stable, long-acting thyroid hormone replacement with a half-life of 7 days permitting once-daily dosing; liothyronine (T3) has a 2.5-day half-life and is reserved for specific situations. Glucocorticoids range from short-acting hydrocortisone (half-life 8–12 hours, 1× potency) to long-acting dexamethasone (half-life 36–54 hours, 25× potency), with biological duration of action far exceeding plasma half-life due to their genomic mechanism; fluorination and hydroxylation patterns determine glucocorticoid-to-mineralocorticoid potency ratios that guide agent selection for specific conditions.</p>
    <p>Adverse effects in hormone pharmacology arise primarily from dose-dependent amplification of normal hormonal physiology or from disruption of physiological feedback regulation. Chronic glucocorticoid therapy produces a clinical syndrome—Cushingoid features including central obesity, moon facies, buffalo hump, striae, easy bruising, proximal myopathy, osteoporosis, hyperglycemia, hypertension, hypokalemia, immunosuppression, and HPA axis suppression—that reflects glucocorticoid receptor activation across all glucocorticoid-responsive tissues. The nurse must be acutely aware that glucocorticoid withdrawal syndrome and adrenal crisis can occur with abrupt discontinuation after prolonged use: patients must be tapered slowly (typically over weeks to months for courses exceeding 3 weeks), must carry medical alert identification, and must receive stress dosing (hydrocortisone 50–100 mg IV every 6–8 hours) during physiological stress such as surgery, serious infection, or trauma. Insulin overdose produces hypoglycemia with neuroglycopenic symptoms (confusion, seizure, coma) and adrenergic symptoms (tremor, tachycardia, diaphoresis); nurses must educate patients and families about recognition, treatment (15 g fast-acting carbohydrate for conscious patients, glucagon 1 mg IM for unconscious patients), and the rule-of-15 in dose adjustment. Thyroid hormone excess with levothyroxine overdose produces thyrotoxicosis symptoms—tachycardia, palpitations, weight loss, tremor, heat intolerance, diarrhea—requiring dose reduction and occasionally beta-blockade for symptom control during titration.</p>
    <p>The clinical landscape of hormone and analog therapeutics extends far beyond simple replacement therapy. GLP-1 receptor agonists (liraglutide, semaglutide, dulaglutide, tirzepatide) have transformed type 2 diabetes management by providing glucose-dependent insulin secretion stimulation, glucagon suppression, gastric emptying delay, and central appetite suppression, with high-dose semaglutide producing 15–20% mean body weight reduction in clinical trials—outcomes rivaling bariatric surgery. SEMAGLUTIDE's (Ozempic/Wegovy) FDA approval for both diabetes and obesity management has created enormous demand and illustrates how incretin pharmacology has shifted from metabolic medicine to a broader therapeutic category. GnRH agonists (leuprolide, goserelin) exploit the pulsatile nature of GnRH secretion: continuous non-pulsatile exposure paradoxically suppresses gonadotropin secretion through receptor downregulation, creating medical castration useful in hormone-sensitive prostate cancer, endometriosis, and uterine fibroids. Nurses managing patients on hormone therapies must understand the pharmacological endpoint for each agent—TSH normalization (target 0.5–2.5 mIU/L for most hypothyroid patients), HbA1c targets informed by individualized guidelines, fasting morning serum cortisol for HPA axis recovery assessment—and must appreciate that hormone titration requires weeks to months for full physiological equilibration, demanding patience and scheduled reassessment.</p>
  </div>

  {drugs.length === 0 && (
    <div class="alert alert-info mb-6">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
      <span>No drugs are currently classified under this therapeutic class. Check back as more drug data is added.</span>
    </div>
  )}

  {drugs.length > 0 && (
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      {drugs.map((drug: any) => (
        <div class={`card card-compact bg-base-100 shadow border border-base-200 ${drug.ismp_high_alert ? 'border-l-4 border-l-error' : ''}`}>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-start gap-1 mb-1">
              <h2 class="card-title text-base font-semibold capitalize mr-auto">
                <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">
                  {drug.generic_name}
                </a>
              </h2>
              {drug.prototype_for && <span class="badge badge-success badge-sm shrink-0">PROTOTYPE</span>}
              {drug.ismp_high_alert && <span class="badge badge-error badge-sm shrink-0">HIGH ALERT</span>}
              {drug.black_box_warnings && drug.black_box_warnings.length > 0 && <span class="badge badge-warning badge-sm shrink-0">BBW</span>}
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-base-content/60 mb-1">
              <span class="font-medium">{drug.drug_class}</span>
              {drug.subclass && <span> — {drug.subclass}</span>}
            </p>
            {drug.mechanism_summary && <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 line-clamp-3">{drug.mechanism_summary}</p>}
            <div class="card-actions justify-end mt-2">
              <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="btn btn-xs btn-outline btn-primary">Profile</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  )}
</SchemaLayout>
